## 1.5. Caching & Performance

* Dependency cache: Mount a dedicated PVC or use a persistent cache volume for Maven .m2 or npm node_modules.
* Docker layer caching: Use Kaniko or BuildKit coupled with a remote registry cache instead of dangerous Docker-in-Docker.
* Parallel stages: Split large test or assembly suites into parallel stages executed across distinct container runtimes.
* Slim images: Use minimal base execution images for agent containers to reduce network image pull times.

------------------------------
## 1.6. Container Build Strategy (Avoid Docker-in-Docker)

* Kaniko: Rootless execution, requires no privileged Docker daemon background process. Safest for Kubernetes.
* BuildKit: Highly performant, supports modern distributed caching structures, and works well in rootless modes.
* Jib: Java-specific artifact creation, builds well-optimized container images directly without needing a Dockerfile.

## 1.6.1. Kaniko Execution Template

container('kaniko') {
    sh '''
    /kaniko/executor \
        --context . \
        --destination registry.example.com/my-app:${BUILD_NUMBER} \
        --cache=true
    '''
}

------------------------------
## 1.7. Security

* RBAC: Create a dedicated Kubernetes ServiceAccount for Jenkins agents configured with minimal required role scopes.
* Credentials: Store enterprise secrets securely inside the Jenkins credentials store or HashiCorp Vault. Never hardcode keys.
* Network policies: Restrict outbound agent pod network transport access to only known designated internal endpoints.
* Pod security: Run containers as non-root profiles and systematically drop unnecessary security capabilities.

securityContext:
    runAsNonRoot: true
    runAsUser: 1000
    fsGroup: 1000

------------------------------
## 1.8. Shared Libraries

@Library('my-shared-lib@main') _
myPipeline(appName: 'my-app', buildTool: 'maven')


* ✅ Centralize pipeline logic: Standardize deployment definitions inside a shared library git repository.
* ✅ Version the library: Explicitly target library code blocks using strict release tags or fixed branch scopes.
* ✅ Avoid duplicating code: Do not replicate standard code sequences across distinct repository configurations.
* ✅ Define common elements: Standardize global pod templates, validation stages, and messaging utility functions.

------------------------------
## 1.9. Pipeline Reliability

* retry and timeout: Wrap inherently flaky communication steps in retry(3) and always set strict step-level timeout values.
* post blocks: Always use post { always { } } structure for cleanups and execution notifications.
* catchError: Prevent non-critical single stage pipeline crashes from blocking execution of vital resource cleanup hooks.
* Idempotent steps: Ensure all underlying automated script actions can be safely executed multiple times.
* Declarative over Scripted: Prefer declarative pipeline definitions to gain clear structural parsing and execution guardrails.

